      <hedline>
        <hl1>After the Second Debate, a New Scorecard</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ruth Grunberg letter protests exclusion of third-party candidates from presidential debates (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Although the Gore-Bush debate on Wednesday night was informative (front page, Oct. 12), I am still frustrated by the total exclusion of third-party candidates. Because they are left out, many important issues are completely ignored by the two major parties, which are controlled by every special interest in the world.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Although the Gore-Bush debate on Wednesday night was informative (front page, Oct. 12), I am still frustrated by the total exclusion of third-party candidates. Because they are left out, many important issues are completely ignored by the two major parties, which are controlled by every special interest in the world.</p>
        <p>Another debate should be added. But the questions should all be submitted by the excluded third parties, which represent alienated and disaffected Americans. Can we really call ourselves a democracy when many people do not vote and feel that their voices are never heard?</p>
        <p>RUTH GRUNBERG  Cortland, N.Y., Oct. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
